===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|acre|lang=enm}}, {{term|aker|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term|æcer||a field, land, that which is sown, sown land, cultivated land; a definite quantitiy of land, land which a yoke of oxen could plough in a day, an acre, a certain quantity of land, strip of plough-land; crop|lang=ang}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*akraz||field}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*h₂éǵros||field}}. Cognate with {{etyl|sco|-}} {{term|acre|lang=sco}}, {{term|aker|lang=sco}}, {{term|acker||acre, field, arable land|lang=sco}}, {{etyl|frr|-}} {{term|ecir||field, a measure of land|lang=frr}}, {{etyl|fy|-}} {{term|eker||field|lang=fy}}, Dutch {{term|akker||field|lang=nl}}, German {{term|Acker||field, acre|lang=de}}, {{etyl|sv|-}} {{term|åker||field|lang=sv}}, {{etyl|is|-}} {{term|akur||field|lang=is}}, Latin {{term|ager||land, field, acre, countryside|lang=la}}, Ancient Greek {{term|ἀγρός||field|tr=agros|lang=grc|sc=polytonic}}. Related also to {{l/en|acorn}}.

